description:
In lichen_lora_l2_set_rx_callback(), user_data is set BEFORE the callback pointer:

```c
k_mutex_lock(&lora_mutex, K_FOREVER);
lora_state.rx_callback_user_data = user_data;
lora_state.rx_callback = cb;
k_mutex_unlock(&lora_mutex);
```

While both writes happen under mutex, the rx_thread reads both atomically:
```c
k_mutex_lock(&lora_mutex, K_FOREVER);
lichen_lora_rx_cb_t cb = lora_state.rx_callback;
void *cb_user_data = lora_state.rx_callback_user_data;
k_mutex_unlock(&lora_mutex);
```

Since both reader and writer hold the mutex, this is actually safe. The mutex provides atomicity. However, the order SHOULD be callback first, user_data second, because if the callback were set first without mutex protection, a reader could invoke the new callback with stale user_data.

Currently protected by mutex, so this is a code quality issue (P3) - the order is confusing but correct. Setting user_data first then callback is actually the safer pattern IF there were no mutex (callback NULL check would fail), so the current code is defensive. Marking as no action needed.
